  %h4.centered
    BipartisanScore Methodology
  BipartisanScore seeks to objectively rate all members of Congress based on their bipartisan actions.  BipartisanScore uses roll votes cast by legislators as the basis to identify and evaluate bipartisan actions.  The evaluation assigns points to each member for each roll vote that is cast in a bipartisan manner.  A legislator's vote is considered to be bipartisan when it differs from the majority position of his or her own party and matches the majority position of the opponent party.  Bipartisan votes in favor of advancing legislation are given additional points, and if the overall outcome of the chamber vote results in advancement of the legislation, then even more points are awarded to the legislator. 
  %h5.centered.highlight
    The BipartisanScore Formula
