    The Bipartisan Factor
  The above formula for BipartisanScore points relies upon the calculation of the Bipartisan Factor.  The Bipartisan Factor is an important component of determining the bipartisanship level of any given vote cast by a legislator.  It is designed to progressively reward legislators that cast votes contrary to his or her own party's majority in order to pass or advance legislation.  The Bipartisan Factor is determined by applying a simple algorithm to each roll vote of each legislator:
  .imgcontainer
    = image_tag("factorAlgorithm.png")
  The above algorithm illustration demonstrates how the Bipartisan Factor progressively rewards legislators that (1) cast a roll vote that differs from their own party's majority position while simulataneously matching the opposing party, (2) vote to advance/pass legislation, and (3) provide the needed effort to affect the final result of the chamber vote to advance/pass legislation.  Keep in mind that per the structure of the BipartisanScore Point formula, if a roll vote cast by a legislator is determined to have a Bipartisan Factor of zero, he or she will not accrue any BipartisanScore points for that vote.  
  %h5.centered.highlight
    Bill Opposition Factor
  In addition to the Bipartisan Factor, the BipartisanScore Point formula relies upon calculation of the Bill Opposition Factor.  The Bill Opposition Factor reflects the net number of legislators from different parties that oppose each other's position on a particular roll vote.  A high Bill Opposition Factor signifies broad party-line voting while a lower Bill Opposition Factor signifies a higher level of bipartisnship amongst legislators.  The BipartisanScore Point formula is designed to reward legislators more when they vote in a bipartisan manner on a highly-partisan bill.  
